RTbySpeedAnalysis

This documents shows how Reaction Times (RT) to a potential hazard may vary depending on driving speed. The dataset presents two speed categories: highway (1) and city (0). A potential hazard is represented by a pedestrians standing on the sidewalk at 4 or 14 degrees eccentricity.

Descriptives

Reaction Times

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.

Conclusions 1

RTs are larger in the High Speed Category (Highway) than in the Low Speed Category (City). RTs also depend on the eccentricity of the potential hazard: objects that are more peripheral are reported later than more central objects.

Cluster Analysis successfully identified all the high speeds events. Potential collisions fell within the High Speed cluster.
